ough a series of illuminating readings, the authors show how Shakespeare was the supreme virtuoso of the second chance and Freud was its supreme interpreter. Both Shakespeare and Freud believed that we can narrate our life stories as tales of transformation, of momentous shifts, constrained by time and place but often still possible. Ranging from The Comedy of Errors to The Winter’s Tale, and from D. W. Winnicott to Marcel Proust, the authors challenge readers to imagine how, as Phillips writes, “it is the mending that matters.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aOpportunity. 0aPsychoanalysis. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh1 aPhillips, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074979340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300277296?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300277296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300277296/original  a978-3-11-074979-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles